However, a past life cannot be remembered, making the cause and effect connection rather mysterious.         Caliph Muslim religious authority; his office is the Caliphate. In Urdu, language of India’s Muslims, Khilafat. Gandhi was a champion of the Khilafat movement.         GOI = Govt of India = the Raj Led by the Governor General who also holds the title Viceroy . These are virtually identical except that Viceroy technically means overlord of the Princely Kingdoms of India; Gov-Gen means overlord of the colonized areas of India. There were some 500+ princely kingdoms, governed like fiefs by a nawab, theoretically independent and indigenous but usually supporters of the Raj; other titles than nawab were used. The Viceroy answered to a Secretary of State in London, who in turn answered to the Prime Minister, servant of the Crown. The Secretary and Viceroy were the highest authority and were always British. The Viceroy had a Legislative Council to advise him. Secretary of State and Viceroy held decisive power in India.          Triplice or Triple Intervention spring 1895, on the heels of the Treaty of Shimonoseki that ends the Sino-Japanese War. The Japanese had very pointed intentions in selecting Shimonoseki to meet the Chinese representative (Li Hongzhang). By this treaty the Manchu Royal House (governing China until 1911) yields Formosa (Taiwan) to Japan, acknowledges the “independence” of Korea, and allows Japan to occupy the Liaodong Peninsula. Note how Japan can control the east coast of Chinese from the vantage of Corea and Taiwan. See map #3.        Liaodong is the little southwest protrusion of Manchurian land into the Yellow Sea west of Corea. The peninsula offers control of the northern Yellow Sea, the water between China and Korea. At the southern tip of Liaodong are two crucial ports Port Arthur and Dairen; and the Trans-Siberian RR had a southern spur down to the port. The peninsula gives access eastward to Seoul, westward to Tientsin and Pekin (using the map’s spellings) and of course northward into the Manchurian heartland. The purpose of the Triplice was to force Japan to give the Liaodong back to China. The explicit threat of war convinced Tokyo to comply, surrender this valuable military and commercial holding, and content itself with its conquests (for the moment).        Below are three maps. Also, you mentioned in class that the Triplices comprised of Russia, Germany, and France. RESPONSE FROM PROF:      I don't recall making a direct Boer-Bengal connection. Indirectly: The Boer War (1899-1902) weakened Britain, one factor contributing to London's reaching out to Tokyo (1902). This Alliance (Anglo-Japanese Alliance) encouraged Japan to attack Russia, which happens in 1904. (Note that “alliance” is a very strong commitment, virtually a marriage of states. A Convention is all Tokyo had with St. Petersburg in 1907.) Japan's defeat of Russia in 1905 took pressure from Russia off India. The Viceroy in Calcutta (Bengal capital and seat of the Raj until 1911), George Curzon, a supporter of Japan against Russia, chooses this moment to push for the partition of Bengal, largely to deepen the split between Muslims and Hindus at a time when the Indian National Congress, now 20 years old, is growing stronger and, pushed by the public, more demanding. Curzon had contempt for the Congress, for shared governance with Indians, and for Indians as a people.        The Partition occurs in 1905 and the Muslim League is founded with British blessing in 1906. Curzon may have felt strengthened with Russia beaten and the Alliance vindicated but the internal factors are uppermost. Note: the Anglo-Japanese Alliance of 1902 does not mention India, while the renewal of the Alliance in 1905 brings India into the security sphere of the Alliance. Some Brits even thought Japanese troops could be brought into India if needed for defense, an absurd idea, for several reasons. (It did not happen.)        As for what Russia was doing in China, I was about to take that up in class. The colonization of Siberia, the building of the Trans-Siberian, and the settlement of Vladivostok are the three components of Russia's eastward march. Significantly, the Trans-Sib was scheduled for completion in 1903, and Japan attacked in 1904. Tokyo saw the RR, which can move troops and heavy weapons quickly, as a mortal threat to its plans to expand in northeast Asia. The Tsar had his eye on Manchuria and Korea too. There is also an important "spiritual" component to all this since the Tsar imagined his Russia as a synthesis of European and Asian culture. I'll say a bit more about this Tuesday.      In the Sino-Japanese War 1894-5 Japan muscles its way onto the Asian continent (Korea) and takes over Taiwan. Britain and US see Russia as the main enemy and thus support Japan. Retaliating, Russia led the Triplice of 1895. Germany followed because it wanted a naval base in Jiaozhou (old spelling Kiaochow) on the south shore of Shandong, and actually envisioned taking over the whole province of Shandong (see map). German naval forces occupied Jiaozhou in 1897. The Manchu Court authorized Russia to hold Port Arthur (enforced gratitude for the Triplice) and Germany to have Jiaozhou 1898-1899. London's apparent willingness to accept these gains prompted the first Open Door Note (by John Hay) in 1899. France joined the Triplice because the Parisian banks were financing Russia and wanted to protect Russian interests and make sure that Russia could pay off its bonds.        Germany’s Jiaozhou base becomes a key issue in WWI, when "civil war in Europe" gave Japan a free hand in Asia, and is a key issue again in the post WWI mass movement in China (the May 4 Movement).
